```yaml
verdict: defend
probe_engaged: yes
new_grade: null
rationale: |
  The counterfactual requires the stolen credential database to contain personal
  accounts named tomcat, nagios, hadoop, pi, ftpuser, and www-data — daemon and
  service-role identifiers that do not appear in personal-credential breaches.
  Credential databases from breached services hold personal handles, email
  prefixes, and real names; filtering such a database cannot produce this exact
  set because the source material does not contain these entries. An attacker
  who "filtered to generic usernames" from a real credential DB would produce
  personal-account residue, not a clean system-account wordlist. Even granting
  the counterfactual's mechanism (deliberate filtering), the resulting behavior
  IS wordlist-based opportunistic scanning — the hypothesis distinction tracks
  mechanism, not attacker intent. The `++` grade for ?opportunistic-scanner holds
  because the named failed-refutation shape (≤2 names OR env-specific names) did
  not materialize, and the observed username profile is structurally inconsistent
  with credential-database provenance.
```
